<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7309&amp;p=71864#p71864</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7309&amp;p=71864#p71864"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[SuperNSF PCM+PSG driver]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7309&amp;p=71864#p71864"><![CDATA[
Yes, indeed it's amazing.  I was reading <a href="http://battleofthebits.org/academy/GroupThread/2397/SuperNSF+and+SuperNSF%2B/" class="postlink">another page</a> which seemed to highlight a flamewar about whether or not it's "Legitimate" to use mixed PCM in NSF competitions.  (My opinion: it isn't)<br /><br />The obvious problem is that it seems next to impossible to use this engine in a game, except for a static screen with no tricks.  The "Rickrolled" demo showed us that you can still pull off one PPU write and scroll every frame even with streaming PCM playing, but I wouldn't throw in any OAM updates in there.<br /><br />Edit: I wonder if this could be done with a cycle-based IRQ mapper?  It takes about 41 CPU cycles to respond to an IRQ and play a pre-mixed sample.  So if you make the sample rate 16384Hz, playback takes 37% CPU usage.  Mixing happens in another thread, is it fast enough to keep up?<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=53">Dwedit</a> — Fri Dec 24, 2010 7:34 am</p><hr />
]]></content>
